-- allium: 3
-- turbo_kv_residual_window.allium

-- Scope: residual-window KV-cache overlay — maintain a separate
-- fp16/bf16 ring-buffer copy of the K vector for the most recent
-- N positions, alongside the core quantised K cache. Every token
-- is still quantised into the main cache; the overlay exists
-- in parallel.
--
-- Composes on top of turbo-kv-4b.allium and turbo-kv-3b.allium
-- (and any other lossy K-cache scheme). The overlay writes do
-- not affect the main cache's contents or correctness in any
-- way — they are a second storage path maintained for a future
-- attention read path that can consult them for recent tokens.
--
-- Citable sources:
--
--   [PAPER]       Zandieh et al., arxiv 2504.19874. Paper does
--                 not model a residual window — it treats the full
--                 sequence as a single quantisation batch.
--
--   [TONBI-V3]    tonbistudio/turboquant-pytorch compressors_v3.py.
--                 Introduces residual_window as a core V3 concept.
--                 Measured evidence (README needle-in-haystack on
--                 Llama 3.2):
--                   K4/V4 rw=128:  EXACT at 2K and 4K ctx
--                   K4/V4 rw=0:    MISS (garbage output)
--                   K4/V2 rw=0:    MISS
--                 The rw=0 MISS result is the critical evidence:
--                 symmetric 4-bit K quantisation without a residual
--                 window fails the most basic retrieval task.
--                 README: "What doesn't work: 3-4 bit compression
--                 without a residual window produces garbage, same
--                 as V2."
--
--   [QUANT.CPP]   Does NOT implement a residual window. Our
--                 llama.cpp port addresses this gap.
--
-- Difference from [TONBI-V3] framing: [TONBI-V3] is an eviction
-- model — recent tokens are held in fp16 and quantised on eviction
-- past the window. This spec is an *overlay* model — every token
-- is quantised into the main cache as usual, and a separate
-- fp16/bf16 ring buffer additionally holds the last N K vectors
-- per stream per layer. The overlay is redundant storage, not
-- the authoritative copy.
--
-- Implemented today: the cparams flag, per-layer allocation at
-- context init, the graph-build overlay write on cpy_k, and the
-- dtype auto-resolution. Aspirational and flagged as such below:
-- the attention read path consuming the overlay, the Vulkan port
-- of the overlay write + read, and GGUF state persistence across
-- session save/load. Rules for the aspirational paths appear
-- below with @guidance annotations marking them as not yet
-- witnessed by code.

-- ============================================================
-- External Entities
-- ============================================================

-- One K vector produced for a single (layer, stream, position)
-- by the forward pass. The overlay mirrors this value at the
-- ring-buffer slot for the position.
external entity KVector {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
    layer: Integer
    stream: Integer
    position: Integer
}

-- The context in which the cache lives. Used to bound the
-- residual window against sequence length.
external entity Context {
    n_ctx: Integer
    n_layer: Integer
    n_stream: Integer
}

-- ============================================================
-- Enumerations
-- ============================================================

-- Runtime overlay storage dtype. The CLI may accept an "auto"
-- sentinel, but that is resolved into one of these two values
-- before the overlay is allocated. See ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto.
enum OverlayDtype { f16 | bf16 }

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- Size of the ring-buffer overlay, in tokens. [TONBI-V3]
    -- default is 128. 0 disables the overlay entirely (no
    -- allocation, no writes, no reads). Measured needle-in-
    -- haystack evidence in [TONBI-V3] puts 128 at the knee for
    -- 4-bit K at the 3B-parameter scale on Llama 3.2.
    residual_window: Integer = 128

    -- Runtime overlay dtype. Concrete values only; the "auto"
    -- CLI sentinel is resolved by ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto before
    -- reaching this parameter.
    overlay_dtype: OverlayDtype = f16
}

-- ============================================================
-- Rules
-- ============================================================

-- Compute the ring-buffer slot for a (stream, position) pair.
-- Load-bearing for downstream reasoning about overwrites,
-- rollback and the overlay read path. The overlay tensor is
-- laid out as [n_embd_k_gqa, residual_window, n_stream]; the
-- flat slot index is stream * residual_window + (position mod
-- residual_window). The modulo is a black-box function since
-- the Allium expression language does not include %.
rule ComputeOverlaySlot {
    when: OverlaySlotRequested(stream, position)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0

    let slot = stream * config.residual_window + modulo(position, config.residual_window)

    ensures: OverlaySlotResolved(
        stream: stream,
        position: position,
        slot: slot
    )
}

-- On each decoded token, the K vector for that token is written
-- into the overlay at the ring-buffer slot for (stream, position).
-- This runs in parallel with the main cache's own append; it does
-- not displace, gate, or depend on the main-cache write.
--
-- Writes overwrite any stale data at the same slot (ring wrap);
-- at position p the slot (p mod residual_window) for that stream
-- last held data from position (p - residual_window).
rule AppendOverlayRow {
    when: KVectorProduced(k)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: k.count > 0

    ensures: OverlaySlotResolved(
        stream: k.stream,
        position: k.position,
        slot: k.stream * config.residual_window + modulo(k.position, config.residual_window)
    )

    ensures: OverlayWriteCommitted(
        layer: k.layer,
        stream: k.stream,
        position: k.position,
        data: k.data
    )

    @guidance
        -- Implementation: the graph-build path calls
        -- cpy_k_window(k_cur, k_window_idxs, il) alongside
        -- cpy_k for the main cache. The dtype of the stored
        -- bytes matches config.overlay_dtype after resolution.
}

-- Auto-resolution of config.overlay_dtype when the CLI passes
-- the "auto" sentinel: inspect the model's native K projection
-- float type and pick BF16 if any model weights are BF16, F16
-- if all float weights are F16 or F32, and BF16 as a safe
-- upgrade when weights are quantised with no F16 fallback.
-- Fires once at context initialisation before any overlay
-- allocation occurs.
rule ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto {
    when: OverlayDtypeAutoRequested(context, model_has_bf16_weights, model_has_only_float_weights)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0

    ensures:
        if model_has_bf16_weights:
            OverlayDtypeResolved(context: context, dtype: bf16)
        else if model_has_only_float_weights:
            OverlayDtypeResolved(context: context, dtype: f16)
        else:
            OverlayDtypeResolved(context: context, dtype: bf16)

    @guidance
        -- The sentinel handling is a CLI concern; this rule
        -- describes the observable resolution that tests can
        -- verify. See open question on whether the rule belongs
        -- in config defaults instead.
}

-- Aspirational attention-read rule: reconcile the main
-- (quantised) cache with the overlay for the most recent
-- residual_window positions. At query time, for each attended
-- position in the last residual_window of the sequence, the
-- attention read prefers the overlay K over the dequantised
-- main cache K. Positions older than residual_window are
-- served from the main cache only.
--
-- NOT YET IMPLEMENTED. Writes into the overlay happen on every
-- decode, but the FA / attention read path does not consult
-- the overlay yet.
rule ReadKVRecentFromOverlay {
    when: ReadKVForAttention(query_position, attended_position, stream, seq_len)

    requires: config.residual_window > 0
    requires: attended_position > seq_len - config.residual_window
    requires: attended_position <= seq_len

    ensures: AttentionKeySource(
        query_position: query_position,
        attended_position: attended_position,
        source: overlay
    )

    @guidance
        -- Aspirational read-path rule. Open question on
        -- two-pass FA + LSE merge vs. single-pass assembled-K
        -- is unresolved; neither structure is yet in code.
}

-- Aspirational companion: attended positions older than the
-- residual window are served from the quantised main cache.
rule ReadKVTailFromMainCache {
    when: ReadKVForAttention(query_position, attended_position, stream, seq_len)

    requires: attended_position <= seq_len - config.residual_window

    ensures: AttentionKeySource(
        query_position: query_position,
        attended_position: attended_position,
        source: main_cache
    )

    @guidance
        -- Aspirational. When residual_window = 0 the
        -- ReadKVRecentFromOverlay rule's requires fails for
        -- every position, and this rule covers the whole
        -- sequence (equivalent to the currently implemented
        -- behaviour where every read is from the main cache).
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants
-- ============================================================

-- The residual window must fit in the context and be
-- non-negative. Zero disables the overlay.
invariant ResidualWindowWithinContext {
    for c in Contexts:
        config.residual_window >= 0 and config.residual_window <= c.n_ctx
}

-- The overlay dtype must be a concrete float type at runtime.
-- The "auto" CLI sentinel must be resolved (by
-- ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto) before this invariant is checked.
invariant OverlayDtypeIsFloat {
    config.overlay_dtype in {f16, bf16}
}

-- SWA composition: when a sliding-window-attention layer is
-- stacked with a non-SWA base cache in a hybrid memory, the
-- overlay is meaningful only on the non-SWA side. The SWA
-- side runs with residual_window = 0 for its own cache. This
-- is enforced at cache construction; the hybrid-memory spec
-- owns the per-layer SWA flagging. Listed here as a scope
-- note rather than an expression-bearing invariant because
-- per-layer SWA typing lives outside this spec.

-- ============================================================
-- Actor Declarations
-- ============================================================

-- The overlay inspector is a test-boundary actor used to peek
-- at raw overlay bytes to verify write correctness. No
-- production caller takes this role.
actor OverlayInspector {
    identified_by: Context where n_layer > 0
}

-- ============================================================
-- Surfaces
-- ============================================================

-- Introspection API for verifying overlay writes. Exposes the
-- raw overlay bytes at a specific (layer, stream, slot) and
-- the byte size of one slot so callers can allocate a
-- receiving buffer. Writes are visible through this surface
-- after AppendOverlayRow fires.
surface OverlayPeek {
    facing inspector: OverlayInspector

    context ctx: Context

    exposes:
        ctx.n_layer
        ctx.n_stream

    provides:
        PeekOverlaySlot(inspector, ctx, layer, stream, slot)
        QueryOverlaySlotByteSize(inspector, ctx, layer)

    @guarantee WritesObservableAfterAppend
        -- After AppendOverlayRow has committed a write for a
        -- given (layer, stream, position), PeekOverlaySlot at
        -- the resolved slot returns those bytes until the
        -- next write wraps into the same slot.

    @guarantee SlotByteSizeMatchesDtype
        -- QueryOverlaySlotByteSize returns n_embd_k_gqa
        -- multiplied by the per-element byte size of
        -- config.overlay_dtype (2 bytes for f16 and bf16).
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open Questions
-- ============================================================

open question "Residual window size tuning: [TONBI-V3] defaults to 128 and reports it as the knee of the quality curve at model scales around 3B. Larger models or head_dim=256 configurations (Qwen3.5 9B) may need a larger window; smaller models may tolerate less. No public measurement campaign at our target sizes."

open question "Sliding vs fixed-start window: [TONBI-V3] implements the rolling-tail semantics (most recent N tokens overlaid in fp16). An alternative would be a fixed initial-tokens window (first N tokens in fp16 for the attention-sink / first-few-tokens phenomenon literature). This spec models the rolling-tail variant only."

open question "Interaction with quant.cpp Variant F multi-block split: the core spec (turbo-kv-4b.allium) inherits the per-128-element sub-block split. The residual window acts at the token level (rows); it is orthogonal to the within-row quantisation granularity. Composition should be clean, but the interaction has not been empirically tested."

open question "Auto-resolution placement: ResolveOverlayDtypeAuto is modelled as a rule because config defaults in Allium support only arithmetic over references and literals, and the auto-resolve logic inspects model weight types. A cleaner framing might be a dedicated config-default expression form, or a separate resolution phase. Left as a rule for now."

open question "Overlay representation at the RoPE boundary: the overlay stores whatever k_cur holds at the point cpy_k would have stored it. On standard K caches this is post-RoPE; on pre-RoPE-store caches (turbo-kv-4b stores pre-RoPE and RoPE-at-read) it is pre-RoPE. Whether the attention read path should standardise on one representation — and what MTP rollback must preserve — is unresolved."

open question "Read-path structure: should attention over a recent-overlay plus quantised-tail cache use two-pass FA with LSE merge (one pass per source, merged softmax denominators), or single-pass with an assembled-K tensor spliced at query time? Merge granularity and cross-backend portability are at stake. Not yet prototyped."

open question "Rollback semantics: seq_rm (sequence-position removal) currently does not touch the overlay. Rolled-back positions retain stale ring-buffer data until overwritten. This is harmless today (no reader) but becomes observable once the attention-read path consumes the overlay. MTP draft-rejection and prompt rewind are the concrete callers that force a decision."

open question "Persistence across session save/load: should the overlay participate in state_write / state_read on llama_memory_i? The in-memory ring buffer is lost across session-resume and server checkpoints today. Implications for long-running server deployments and multi-turn evaluation harnesses."

open question "Cross-backend equivalence: does the overlay require its own rule in turbo_kv_4b_backend.allium, or is it covered by that spec's general 'all backends produce the same output given the same inputs' invariant? Does the two-pass FA read path need its own cross-backend validation once it exists?"
